The major changes are:

Global policies: policies located in config/policies are now accessible through the entire app using the global.myGlobalPolicy syntax in routes.json files
Restricted scope policies: policies used without prefix from a routes.json file are restricted to the current API or plugin scope
Plugins policies: policies located in plugin/myPlugin/config/policies are now accessible through the entire app using the plugins.myPlugin.myPluginPolicy syntax
policies folders and files are now located in config folders
policies are now part of the config objects

Documentation
Global policies
From now, you can define global policies which are reusable through your entire app.
Usage
Define your policy:
// ./config/policies/isAuthenticated.js
'use strict';

/**
 * `isAuthenticated` policy.
 */

module.exports = async (ctx, next) => {
  // Add your before logic here.

  await next();

  // Add your after logic here.
};
Usage from an API or from a plugin:
// ./api/car/routes.json
{
  "routes": [
    {
      "method": "GET",
      "path": "/car",
      "handler": "Car.find",
      "config": {
        "policies": [
          "*isAuthenticated"
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
}
Scoped policies
A policy defined in an API or plugin is usable only from this API or plugin. You don't need any prefix to use it.
Usage
Define your policy:
// ./api/car/config/policies/carPolicy.js
'use strict';

/**
 * `carPolicy` policy.
 */

module.exports = async (ctx, next) => {
  // Add your before logic here.

  await next();

  // Add your after logic here.
};
Usage from the API or from a plugin:
// ./api/car/routes.json
{
  "routes": [
    {
      "method": "GET",
      "path": "/car",
      "handler": "Car.find",
      "config": {
        "policies": [
          "carPolicy"
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
}
Use plugins policies from APIs
Plugins policies are usable from any app API.
Usage
Define your policy:
// ./plugins/auth/config/policies/isAuthenticated.js
'use strict';

/**
 * `isAuthenticated` policy.
 */

module.exports = async (ctx, next) => {
  // Add your before logic here.

  await next();

  // Add your after logic here.
};
Usage from an API:
// ./api/car/routes.json
{
  "routes": [
    {
      "method": "GET",
      "path": "/car",
      "handler": "Car.find",
      "config": {
        "policies": [
          "plugins.auth.isAuthenticated"
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
}
Access policies programmatically
Policies are accessible in the strapi object:

Global policy: strapi.config.myPolicy
API policy: strapi.api.myApi.config.myPolicy
Plugin policy: strapi.plugins.myPlugin.config.myPolicy

Changes have been made with only one goal: performances.

Remove proxy middleware (it's not our role to handle this kind of feature in the core).
Remove SSL middleware (we should provide a good tutorial nginx + Strapi instead).
Override Koa context and response to binding Boom methods into them instead of populating the context on each request.
Override Koa context to bind the new logger into it. It allows the user calls directly the logger through the context.

module.exports = {
  subscribe: async ctx => {
     ctx.log.info('My log');
  }
}

Deactivate security middlewares in the development environment.
Remove Winston and use Pino instead.
The following middlewares can't be deactivated: router, boom, responses because there are required to ensure the server will start correctly.
Expose router before initializing the middlewares which allow them to use it if they need it.
Use the router to serve static assets instead of using koa-static has a standalone middleware.
Remove useless dependencies.

This PR allows associations across ./api models and ./plugins/xxx models. It introduces a new attribute plugin in the models to target a model in a plugin.
Example
To create a relation between Post (that you previously created using the CLI or Content Type Builder)  and User (exposed by the Users & Permissions plugin), you need to update both models and specify in the Post's model that you want to make a relation with the User's model of the Users & Permissions plugin.
./api/post/models/Post.settings.json
{
  "connection": "default",
  "attributes": {
    "title": {
      "type": "string"
    },
    "authors": {
      "collection": "user",
      "via": "posts",
      "plugin": "users-permissions"
    }
  }
}
./plugins/users-permissions/models/User.settings.json
{
  "connection": "default",
  "attributes": {
    "username": {
      "type": "string",
      "minLength": 3,
      "unique": true
    },
    "email": {
      "type": "email",
      "minLength": 6,
      "unique": true
    },
    "provider": {
      "type": "string"
    },
    "password": {
      "type": "password",
      "minLength": 6
    },
    "resetPasswordToken": {
      "type": "string"
    },
    "role": {
      "type": "integer"
    },
    "posts": {
      "collection": "post",
      "via": "authors"
    }
  }
}
Changelog

Update Content Manager requests to retrieve the data coming from the associations.
Update Bookshelf and Mongoose query to manage relationships (add, edit, delete).
Update Content Type Builder to edit a plugin's model.
Ensure a plugin's model cannot be deleted.
Add new configurable attribute key to lock attribute from unwanted deletion in the Content Type Builder.
Add new parameter source in the URL to know if the model is exposed by a plugin or not.

